Step 1: Identify which balance sheet items are considered "quick assets." In this context, quick assets include:
 • Cash on Hand
 • Bank Deposits
 • Interest Receivable
 • Accounts Receivable

Step 2: Get the end-of-period amounts:
 • Cash on Hand = 3,730,866.78
 • Bank Deposits = 3,938,781.80
 • Interest Receivable = 10,811.11
 • Accounts Receivable = 1,562,598.26
 • Total Current Liabilities = 829,755.77

Step 3: Sum the quick assets:
 Quick Assets = 3,730,866.78 + 3,938,781.80 + 10,811.11 + 1,562,598.26 
         = 9,243,057.95

Step 4: Calculate the Quick Ratio:
 Quick Ratio = Quick Assets / Total Current Liabilities
       = 9,243,057.95 / 829,755.77 
       ≈ 11.14

Thus, the Quick Ratio is approximately 11.14.
